<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Sabiaceae" genus="Meliosma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Sabiaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
One female was collected on flowers of the host plant (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37E</figureCitation>
) July 8, 2011 in Wulai, northern Taiwan by Mr Mei-Hua Tsou. The female deposited eggs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37A</figureCitation>
) singly on flowers July 12. Larvae hatched in seven days. The larvae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37B</figureCitation>
) fed on flowers and the larval duration was eleven days. mature larvae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37C</figureCitation>
) burrowed into soil and built underground chambers for pupation. Duration of the pupal stage (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 37" captionStartId="F37" captionText="Figure 37. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta wulaiensis sp. nov. on host plant A egg B third-instar larva C mature larva D pupa E adult F adults: P. wulaiensis sp. nov. (left) and P. ishiharai (right)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure37" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545567" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">37D</figureCitation>
) was eight days.
</paragraph>
